}
```

Two changes from your version:
- `setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, a), ms)` instead of `setTimeout(fn, ms)` — your original handed `fn` straight to `setTimeout`, which always calls it with no arguments (actually with the timer's own junk args), so the last call's `a` was silently dropped.
- The returned function is now a regular `function` rather than an arrow, so `this` is the call-site receiver; `fn.apply(this, a)` forwards it. This matters when the debounced function is a method (`obj.onScroll(...)`). If you never use `this`, `() => fn(...a)` would also work.

